draw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1,1)--(0,1)--cycle);
pair a = (1.25,0)+1.25*dir(60);
pair b = a+1.25*dir(-60);
draw((1.25,0)--a--b--cycle);

[/asy]

output:
(5, Initialize square)
let b = 4.875*dir(-60);
set title("Grouping task: Area of square");
x, y = 0.54*a;
c = sqrt(b^2 - 4*a*b);
set length(round(c));
collect(displayixes(c)), cex=1, col=blackvline[2][-1], fill=none);
hold on;
draw(linewidth(2) * x + 0.08*surf(1*sin(a*pi+c/b) - sqrt(4*a*c/b))));
col=vline[2][0];
hold on;
draw("{\\checkwd}");

The area of the square can be found using the formula A = s^2, where s is the length of the side of the square. The length of a diagonal of the square is equal to half the distance between the corners, which can be found by substituting a similar equation for `\theta` and using `sin`. The area of the square is 4*sin(b/a) - (4a*b^2/sin(a)). Taking `π/180` as a reference angle and substituting `sin(a/2π) = 1`, the area of the square is exactly 12 squares that are also equilateral triangles and have the same perimeter. We can use these 12 square-triangles to calculate when a turnabout will occur each year to form one year.

